<br>
&quot;In the beginning.  The elders promised my people that they would have a sheltered home in the world.  That nature itself would protect them.  As long as the wind blows, the grass grows and the sky is blue.&quot;<br>
<br>
...a cold dry gust of wind blows more tattered trash up the alley from the empty market nearby....<br>
<br>
&quot;I was found abandoned as an infant.  In another trash heap far off from this one.  Found stuffed down into an ash filled dumpster behind the Great Library in the plane of knowledge.  Screaming and covered in blood with my cord tangled around my angry kicking arms and legs.   I suppose that by that time my people's home had already lost the wind of vitality and that the iron shod boots of orcs and the like had trampled most green growing things...for certain one never can see the blue sky any longer in the Faedark...that gift was stolen long ago.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;So I was another abandoned orphan, plucked out of that place by a pair of rough blue skinned hands and arms that wore heavy bracers of steel instead of jewelry.  Adopted by a mother that spent most of her time silent and alone surrounded  by friends that turned into enemies.  Enemies she tried to meet with singing steel.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I was thirteen when my mother's friend brought me news of her death.  Poison the weapon of choice by the coward unwilling to meet her blade...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And so i've watched and i've learned, survived and grown just a little bit older in this cold breathless world of cobblestone and coal blackened rooftops where the sky is never blue. &quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I bring into it no great thing, no great vision or philosophy.  I have no faith that gods or fate will save me.  Life is brief, cruel, brutal and cold.  Without a home of my own in this world, still screaming and angry and often covered in blood. &quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll steal the wind and keep it in a bag.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll rob the green from the world and set it into a gem in the pommel of my blade.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll raze the blue out of the sky and I'll poison my blade with it.&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;I am the Fox Mane'd Riddle.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=foxmane@firionavie>Foxmane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/13/02 5:15:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=645.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Birth of a Riddle.</span><hr size=1> When it rains in Freeport, or when the fog is heavy the black soot coughed up into the sky from ten times a thousand brick chimneys makes the slate roof tiles slick and difficult to negotiate.<br>
<br>
I balanced carefully along the peak of the Academy hall in the western slums.  Rain washed over wide curved roof tiles and spilled in grey and white torrents out of the mouths of stone gargoyles and other ornamentations spaced around the edge of the odd floating structures rooftop.<br>
<br>
My adoptive mother's henchman &quot;Needle&quot; straddled the steep peak of the roof top behind me.  A stout length of rope running from the pair of metal hooks that he now called his hands to where it was fastened around my narrow waist.<br>
<br>
Mother had tasked Needle with teaching me something useful about the way things worked in the world and &quot;teaching me things to help me survive&quot;.    Needle himself was a survivor.  He'd lost both his hands to the axe and block of the Knights of Truth when a burglary he'd been engaged in against an enchantress had gone wrong.  Mother used to tell me that he used to be one of the best thievies anyone could hope to meet before a love affair had, in her words, made him go soft.  I guessed that the twisted coils of sharpened metal he used for hands were a reminder not to make the same mistake twice.  He certainly was never soft to me.<br>
<br>
I was half way across the rooftop when I felt a strong tug on the rope which nearly unseated my balance from the dizzy height.  I looked over my shoulder to where Needle sat straddling the peak of the roof and wrapped in his usual unwashed burlap cloak.  We both had the general appearance of a couple of half drowned beggers.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oi....so what if things go wrong fer ya Riddle me girl...here yer half way to home on this...dangerous job and something changes to make things difficult..maybe impossible...maybe on of yer mates turns on ya..&quot;<br>
<br>
Another tug on the rope, this time it was hard enough to almost pull me off my feet completely.  I weight maybe what..ninety pounds soaking wet...which I was...Needle had me be three times the years, muscle mass and weight.  A third tug of the rope while I was still regaining my balance made me hit the heavy slate shingle hard with my hip.  I dug my small fingers into a nitch in the roofwork and braced.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yer gonna learn..or yer gonna fall off and break that pretty little neck of yers girlie girl.&quot;<br>
<br>
I glanced over at Needle and he let out a hoot loud enough for the watch to hear if anyone was paying attention.  Was he really trying to kill me?  Was he trying to get us both killed?<br>
<br>
Needle snarled and put some back into this next tug.  I had to strain every muscle and grip the hold on the sharp tiles until they cut my fingers and made them bleed.  The soot filled water washed over them making the blood vanish off the rooftop.  I didn't know if I could hang on through another series of hard pulls like that.<br>
<br>
Needle ducked the boot dagger I hurled at his face risking one hand loose to try and give him something to think about..or maybe to hurt him.  I wanted to hurt him then.  While he ducked my belt dagger came out and sliced through the wet rope like it was nothing.  It was a magic blade with a dull blue metal that my mother had given me to wear when i was seven.  Something she'd brought back from one of her long absences.<br>
<br>
I gripped the tiles and crouched blade ready but Needle was already coiling up the rope and chuckling.<br>
<br>
&quot;Lesson learned then girlie girl.  Now see if ya can get yer way across to that other side of this peak without a rope to hold ye safe and get down on yer own as well...I'll be at me usual tavern having a drink..mind yer quick now the watch will be lookin out after all that noise ye made.&quot;<br>
<br>
And just that quickly he was over the side of the building and gone.  I was eleven and alone in a high wind and rain on the top of the Academy of Arcane Sciences, bleeding fingers, dagger in hand and looking like a drowned rat.  I crouched and stopped for a moment, just a moment to catch my breathe and realize that Needle had actually gifted me with something.  I was happy for the first time that I could remember. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=varadox>Varadox</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/13/02 10:45:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=645.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> OOC</span><hr size=1> Good story!<br>
