<br>
A dozen heavy wooden tables and perhaps four times that number of chairs are arrayed before a mud spattered bar with an open air grill off to one side.<br>
<br>
Settled at the entrance to the market area of the slums the Flea is a favored haunt for a collection of changing faces, wandering bards, the usual table of surly dark elves passing around drinks while their collection of undead servants insures that the flea never suffers a shortage of fat, bloated, creeping, buzzing flys.<br>
<br>
Fox was in her usual seat at the bar before opening, taking advantage of the first food to hit the grill, avoiding the inevitable collection of late risers that filled the slum markets when the sun was more fully awake.<br>
<br>
Murgen, a barbarian born with a twisted leg and an even more broken and twisted arm served as the Flea's seeming owner and operator.  He shuffled over with a tin plate of steaming roasted vegetables and...a meat something that still had bits of...fur..attached.  Fox flicked the meat to the side of her plate and worked at the more edible bits.  She pushed a small collection of loot over to Murgen who served both as chef and as fence for the local slums. She waved off the flys from her food.<br>
<br>
While Murgen pawed through her latest finds and slowly set a growing pile of silver and a few gold onto the counter of the bar, Fox watched the market go through its usual yawning, stretching, getting ready for a new day routing.  Of course this signaled the end of Fox's day and she contemplated the warm if somewhat moldly smelling corner she'd staked out to curl up into later.  Well away from people and creatures.  A lost corner of the slums that even the rats had forgotten about.<br>
<br>
She spent days now, occasionally weeks at a stretch without speaking a word.  She had no illusion of friendships.  Night passed after night.  She staggered the evenings she worked to make it more difficult for the watch to pin her down.  She changed her targets and her routine so the Captain couldn't pin her activities on just one person and encourage him to press for a more aggressive hunt.<br>
<br>
Of course she could plot a more lucrative job.  Maybe go after one of the homes in the wealthy districts of the city but that would cause a stir.  While it meant more profits and a better life to be sure it also meant leaving the city and moving to another area at least for a good long while.  Muggings and petty larsons, muddy back alley murders and the like didn't turn much when it came to real loot.  But it was something she knew.  It was a life she understood.<br>
<br>
She flexed her small fingers and traced little circles in the water gathered on the surface of the bar in front of herself pondering the world and her place in it.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=foxmane@firionavie>Foxmane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/18/02 4:32:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=645.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Needle's Death and the Guild</span><hr size=1> Fox crouched in the usual freezing late afternoon downpour leaning her back against the broken brick walls of a tenament in the Freeport slums.<br>
<br>
Needle was dead.<br>
<br>
His corpse sat across the muddy alleyway from her with his legs sprawled out before him and his body twisted in the death grip of rigormortis that betrayed that he'd been dead longer than several hours but less than a few days.<br>
<br>
Enormous black flys from the slum's market crawled in and out of his gaping mouth, fixed in a scream.  His blood had boiled out of his eyes, ears and nose in a great gout before he'd finally died.  Drying thick and sticky over his frigid corpse.<br>
<br>
Magic had killed him.<br>
<br>
Fox knew the type.  Tears ran down out of her eyes vanishing in the rain and her shoulders shook a little but she didn't make any sound beyond that.  <br>
<br>
Needle's death marked a milestone in her own limited existence.  The little wood elf shifted over next to Needle and avoided his stare which seemed to glare at her as she carefully rifled his belongings.<br>
<br>
Needle's hooked hands were missing.  The replacements taken.  But his belt pouch, the coin he'd been carrying and a tarnished old engagement ring he wore on a string around his neck were still with him.<br>
<br>
Fox chewed a length of her dark red hair in thought as she pocketed those items.  Not a robbery then.  Someone had come for Needle specifically.  Someone who had taken Needle's hooks as a trophy.  A reminder of their victory.  That was something to file away in her memory for later.<br>
<br>
Fox sat back on her haunches for a moment longer pondering what to do next.  Needle was simply too heavy for her to move easily alone.  If she was found dragging his corpse out of the muddy alleyway the watch would just as quickly blame her for the deed than look for another.<br>
<br>
Fox flipped out her dagger and snicked off a length of Needle's gray'd hair.  Then she stood and looked down at her dead teacher and mentor in the rain.<br>
<br>
&quot;There are worse things than dying Needle. &quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Goodbye.&quot;<br>
<br>
She turned on her heel and her small body was quickly lost in the mazelike alleyways of the slums. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=foxmane@firionavie>Foxmane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/19/02 7:20:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=645.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A new teacher...</span><hr size=1> Fox slipped through the market stalls of the Freeport slum balancing from one wooden slat to another.  Walking wood slat to wooden slat was just about the only reliable way to keep from stepping into grey soggy clay up to your hip in the slums.<br>
<br>
Her adopted mother was coming to visit today.  It was likely at any rate.  Her absent guardian parent, if that was indeed what she could be called, never seemed to forget Fox's birthday.  The one day each year that marked the day that Fox had been lifted bloody and screaming as an abandoned infant out of a rubbish pile.<br>
<br>
Fox stopped on a narrow wooden four by four slat and stared at the bar of the Flea.  In her usual chair sat a Tier Dal acquintance of her mothers.  A hard looking thief himself that went under the name of Cinnistyr.  The master thief was a part of a circle of friends that mother rarely spoke of.  Some dark business she was engaged in in the world beyond Fox.  Beyond what she called home and family.  Cinnistyr stood almost immediately.  It was clear that he'd been waiting there for Fox.  Her mind raced for a moment.  Should she run?  Mother's friends had a habit of turning up dead or turning up looking for blood one or the other.<br>
<br>
Something about the way the fellow carried himself told Fox that running would not do her much good.  She closed her hand over a rusty thrusting blade carried under her cloak.  She would not run.  She would close the distance and see what he had to say and if something bad happened she'd have one chance to bury that rusty dagger into his throat.<br>
<br>
Fox balanced over to where Cinnistyr waited for her.  Stood at his feet looking up at him through her usual tangle of thick curly red hair.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your really not much to look at.&quot; <br>
<br>
Cinnistyr's way of saying an introduction.<br>
<br>
Fox shrugged.  She didn't pretend to be pretty.  Not here, not in the slums where it was a liability more than a gift.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your mother is dead.&quot;<br>
<br>
Fox stared through Cinnistyr.  His further words lost in a distant muffle pushed down and away by the weight of grief, terrible grief that dropped through Fox's belly like a heavy stone.  She imagined she saw her own heart and soul drop out of her body and down into the rotten grey soaked clay beneath her feet.<br>
<br>
She was vaguely aware of more words and an odd pat on the shoulders from the Tier Dal.  Being led out of the muck and the rain and throught the streets of the slums up into the more cobbled stone walks of the western city.   Pushed into a dry bed by rough cold hands and a presence that watched her while she stared at the ceiling.<br>
<br>
The world moved on without regard for the grief of a nobody over the death of one of a thousand shadows.  The room grew dark and lighter and darker again.  It wasn't until some undisclosed time had passed that Fox gathered back to herself.  Her sightless eyes could see and sounds returned to her ears.<br>
<br>
Cinnistyr sat in a high backed wooden chair before a fire that cast shadows throughout the room.  She watched him and saw that he mused with a noble and furrowed brow.  He became aware of her.  Of her return to the painful world of loss.  The world of Freeport at night.  Her world.<br>
<br>
&quot;She asked me to give you some things.  She asked me to watch out for you as she had.  I've never understood your mother fully.  But.  It was her last request.  So I will see what I can do.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cinnistyr gestured at a shadow'd pile heaped near the fireplace.  There in the glow of the flickering flames gleamed her mother's armor.  Also her mother's sword which was named Gal'drasil and which had a reputation for howling and calling for blood in the presence of Gnolls and Orcs and things.  They were her mother's only true belongings.  It was a clear sign that she was indeed gone. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=daonwolf>Daon Wolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/20/02 1:55:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=645.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A new teacher...</span><hr size=1> OOC: I like this character. I hope to read more in the future. keep writing <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
