Daon Wolf <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=foxmane@firionavie>Foxmane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/20/02 3:26:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=645.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Job ( part one )</span><hr size=1> Cinnistyr perched himself on Fox's usual chair waiting for her to arrive at the Filthy Flea.  It was raining again.  The canvas tarp that served as the Flea's roof had seen so much rain that sections of it had begun to rot completely through.  There were at least a dozen holes in the tarp and the general atmosphere of rotten, cold, soaking, miserable weather was comfortable enough for the Tier Dal to help keep his mood improved.<br>
<br>
The tavern hostler named Murgen limped around behind the bar and worked to get set up for the coming day's business.  Cinnistyr enjoyed the entertainment of watching a crippled barbarian slide around in the mud doing menial chores for a moment before he felt a familiar poke at his shoulder.<br>
<br>
Fox had just slipped onto the stool next to his.  She was very small.  A white streak ran through her red hair and her sparkling black eyes and small build made the name of Foxmane very fitting for her.   Fox pulled back the hood of her waterproof lizard scale cloak and gestured at a pair of bags at Cinnistyr's feet.<br>
<br>
&quot;Isn't it a little early to be handing out Yule gifts to the children of the slums Cinnistyr?&quot;<br>
<br>
Cinnistyr grunted.  He lifted one of the heavy bags and sat it onto the counter with the jangle of metal coins.  Fox's eyes grew a notch bigger.<br>
<br>
&quot;Go ahead and open it.&quot;<br>
<br>
Fox carefully checked the bag for traps.  She wasn't stupid after all.  Then slowly lifted the opening and peered at the jumbled pile of copper and silver, gold and even some platnum inside.<br>
<br>
Cinnistyr dropped the other bag onto the bar counter and dumped it's contents out with a thud.  An enormous red bearded head rolled on the counter for a moment before coming to rest.  It was very large.  Too large to be the head of an ogre or troll.<br>
<br>
&quot;The loot came off of one of these Hill Giants.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cinnistyr turned the head so Fox could get a better look at it.<br>
<br>
&quot;They seem to be congregated around a particular stone tower in the mountains of rathe far from here.  It seems they travel to that one hill from great distances carrying with them enough coin to suggest that they are either there to make some sort of an offering, or to purchase supplys or some other important activity.&quot;<br>
<br>
Fox drummed her fingertips on the bar counter.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aren't giants rather dangerous?&quot;<br>
<br>
Cinnistyr nodded.  &quot;Xas.  Indeed.  It takes an entire group of mercenarys to pull one or two down.  And a nice haul it is too...except.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Except if they are bringing treasure to the hill to buy something then whoever they are buying from has a much much bigger collection of their wealth than any single giant.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Exactly.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cinnistyr and Foxmane looked at each other for a long time as Murgen skulked and the rain showered down on the empty streets of the slums. <br>
<br>
&quot;I can be ready in an hour to leave.&quot;  Fox got up and pulled up the hood of her cloak.<br>
<br>
&quot;Alright..make it thirty minutes and I'll meet you at the west gate of the city.&quot;<br>
<br>
Life had a funny way of changing course suddenly Fox thought as she hopped from one wooden slat to the other through the market and up the rickety wooden steps to her hidden nook.<br>
<br>
Just when you think things are settled down something else happens to change...well..everything.  Fox wondered what sort of change this would be.  For the better or for the worse.  She rifled through her few belongings picking the important ones to bring with.  Hiding the remainder behind a few loose bricks in the wall of the ruined tenement flat.<br>
<br>
The young girl looked around the lonely broken down room that had been her home for six years of her life once from the hole in the wall that served as entrance and ran off into the rain to meet Cinnistyr.<br>
<br>
