<br>
The wagons had been moving again for about two hours.  The forest showed no real signs of ending although their slow progress upwards, ever upwards had brought with it a colder cut in the chill of the air and a roaring noise of wind moving through the tops of the trees that heralded mountains and mountain passages not many miles ahead.<br>
<br>
&quot;Won't be long now.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Tier Dal merchant spoke to her for the first time since she had joined the caravan with Cinnistyr three days previously.  He kicked his horse, a beautiful black steed, so that it strode next to Fox, nearly on top of her.  He sneered down his slender nose at her as if merely looking at her face gave him the sudden impulse to retch himself.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wear this.  I've seen to it that your master has one as well.&quot;<br>
<br>
It was a simple black medallion on a silver chain.<br>
<br>
Sorcery.<br>
<br>
The image of Needle's gaping screaming frozen visage from the alleyways seered through Fox's mind in warning.  Still the Tier Dal was only offering this because he thought she was a slave of Cinnistyrs.  It was slightly less likely that it was meant to kill either of them outright.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wear it and live or throw it away and die.  Your choice slave...but decide quickly.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Tier Dal merchant kicked his horse forward and road past the front of the column and up the road.  Scouting ahead?  Fox drummed small fingers on the pommel of her rapier again.<br>
<br>
Six large wagons, their teams, teamsters and ferriers and a dozen human guards creaked and jangled up the cart path, winding ever higher as dusk settled firmly over the Kithicor Forest.  Both men and beasts showed signs of worry.  Snorting and shying away from the forest and pressing themselves towards the center of the cartpath as much as possible.<br>
<br>
As darkness crept over the land it seemed to Fox that the Kithicor Forest slowly devoured itself through a slow rising grey mist that soon clutched every piece of the woodland in a cold murky grasp.<br>
<br>
The caravan rumbled onward until a cry was raised from the front of the column and the milita guardsmen rallied together at the front of the wagons.  One of the guardsmen had seen something staggering in the fog in the path of the wagons.  Fox climbed onto the top of the front wagon and stood on tiptoes peering over the gathering of soldiers on horse but saw nothing.<br>
<br>
It was possible the guardsmen were simply scaring themselves witless from the ghost stories they had been trading back and forth ever since setting foot into the forest.<br>
<br>
