<br>
Things.  Began to move.<br>
<br>
Fox's tall pointed ears twitched as they caught the sound in the grasses and over twigs.  Here there, all around the caravan.<br>
<br>
Swords were drawn and the sergeant leading the militia bellowed.  &quot;Ready!&quot;<br>
<br>
Fox tried to focus on the noises closest to her.  Paused for a second and then slipped the black medallion the absent merchant had handed to her over her neck.  She hoped CInnistyr had his on as well and that he wouldn't sleep through a combat.<br>
<br>
Her small tan hand reached back over her shoulder an snatched the feathers and nock of an arrow pulling it back on the heavy silk of her bow.  The bow string creaked as she drew the arrow back and focused on the evident stumbling sounds coming out of the forest towards her..<br>
<br>
It was human once.  Grey or ash white skin and a black mouth filled with broken and cracked teeth.  A maw that gaped impossibly wide as the thing snarled at her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Fil'in'inthwi!&quot;<br>
<br>
Fox sang the rune marked on her mother's bow.  White blue flame shot along the shaft of the arrow and flared the brighter when the shaft was loose.  It was as if a star had been born in the darkness of that wooded hollow and burned white hot and brilliant as it struck home into the open mouth of the ghoul.<br>
<br>
Everywhere the creatures appeared.  Everywhere the party of the caravan was engaged.  Undead were broken assunder with axe and sword and staff and spear, their limbs hewn and their head removed to lay twitching on the black stained grass.<br>
<br>
But the number and power of the undead waxed with the deepening of the night with every passing moment and the valiant and then desperate militia and caravan workers were drawn down under a sea of fangs and claws and ancient corruption.<br>
<br>
Cinnistyr burst forth out of his wagon two blades gleaming in the darkness to match the glow of his Tier Dal eyes.  He forced his way through a crowd of undead trying to gorge themselves on two militia hacking and thrusting like an angry god.<br>
<br>
Somehow.  The fury of his constant assault brought him to where Fox stood at the edge of the caravan gripping her last arrow to her mother's bow.  A sea of undead slowly shuffled around them.  Yet they did not attack in force.  Cinnistyr cut the hands and heads off of those that were enthusiastic enough to try and snatch at them.<br>
<br>
&quot;ENOUGH!  BACK!&quot;<br>
<br>
The command was in Tier Dal.  A language that Fox knew well.  The undead snarled but obeyed.  Fox and Cinnistyr craned their necks to find the captain of these monsters seated on his black steed somewhat transformed in the darkness of the forest.<br>
<br>
